I didn't quite get it on the first try, but my second guess for 17D did the trick.

@Steve 

Recent US "policy"?

REASON TREASON

@RIch Garella 

That sounds plausible. However, in Poland koncesja is strictly a permit issued by the government (to operate an airline, for example, or run a power plant), so the context is different, if not unrelated.

@Bobby Salmon 

Thank you. You posted as I was writing my second comment.

@Andrzej

ALCOA is the Aluminum Company of America. Very big in Pittsburgh for years, back when America was a manufacturing powerhouse. 

PRAT is actually British English, hence the reference to Newcastle.

@Teresa 

Yes, obviously, but I still didn't know it 🤷

Thank you for the explanation of ALCOA. It's good to know the name is not as random as I thought it was 🙂

@Andrzej

You missed something in the theme that would have helped your solve.  

All of the paired words are identical except for the PRO and CON part.  Once you had PRO(CESSIONS), the other word had to be CON(CESSIONS).

@Andrzej,

I was thinking about you while I was doing much of this puzzle. This was fairly hard for me to figure out what they were looking for, and I kept thinking, “I wonder how far Andrzej will get with this today”. I thought the cluing was harder than a typical Sunday. 

It was PROTESTANT CONTESTANT that finally revealed the theme to me. I loved that clue!

@Andrzej

Try to file ALCOA in the crossword part of your brain because I've seen it more than once in these puzzles.  It's got a lot of handy vowels.

Thanks for the explanations of how the meanings of these words differ between Polish and English.

@Beth 

I don't care about brands - or the contrarian hater of late-stage capitalism part of me doesn't, which is most of me - so I make it a point to not remember them 🤪

Also, even though I now know where the name comes from, it doesn't seem like something I would remember even if I wanted: my memory is notoriously bad, and recalling something as unnatural as ALCOA is probably simply beyond my ability. Several years of heavy drinking to deal with the horror of my mother's cancer may have had something to do with this mental deterioration.

@Bobby Salmon 

Yeah, it took me about a year of marinating in Wednesday puzzles until I felt confident enough to even try Friday or Saturday.  (Thursday is a think unto itself.)

Congratulations!

@Jane Wheelaghan

"Going TO POT and PRAT (and pratfall) are common in the UK."

I believe that's why PRAT was clued as "Newcastle ninny," indicating that it's UK slang. We don't really use it much in the U.S. (Of course, there is a Newcastle in Delaware, and probably other states.)

@Lewis
Do I need to pay you royalties if I pint out the neat PuzzPair© of KOD and OKD? 
(Still want that "E," tho.)

@Xword Junkie

Thanks. I didn't actually bother looking it up, so your information is new to me, and makes sense of the clue. 
My solve was also hampered by my reading of MDW as WMD for a while, which was alarming.

@Bill

For your first nit:

Ask Pope Francis.

@Bill
So interesting.
My father used to use 'yonder' quite a lot: "It's over yonder"and 'yon' is still used in Scots dialect now: "See yon boy over there."

@Xword Junkie 
The 1st theme clue annoyed me as well. It's such an easy fix on the clue to make it correct.  

Loved TAOOFPOOH and fondly remembered reading it.

@john ezra
I suggest that these organizations are trying to be clever and fashion-forward with their "word of the year" nominations, and not necessarily engaging in exhaustive research. (Allyship would be a prime example of that.) I would not expect to see "reciprocal" appear on any such list this year, but it certainly should.

Stop trying to make "fetch" happen.

@Linda Jo
