This puzzle wasn't "too easy" for this American.  I needed twenty four cheats.  While I can appreciate its cleverness, it was not created for people like me.  (But I complain anyway.)

I hope that Brit drama makes it to PBS, it sounds very interesting!

@Oikofuge
The Swansea news must have passed me by. I’m aware of Port Talbot, but otherwise ignorant of heavy industry.
TONY STARK was a gimme due to my then teenage son and his obsession with all things Stan Lee.

@Jim
Don't parse the clue as "linear array in algebra," but "array in linear algebra":
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#Matrices" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra#Matrices</a>

@Jim

Would you interpret a "Multivariable calculus course" to be a course in multivariable calculus, or a calculus course with multiple variables: time offered, classroom size, etc?

I think the problem is yours, Jim.

@Jim

Linear Algebra is a branch of mathematics about algebraic equations with single power terms, like "4x + 3y + 7z = 5". In that example you would need three equations to solve three unknowns. The best way to approach it is to place all three equations in a matrix and use matrix manipulation to solve. The matrix is square because of the multiple linear equations. 

In short, there's nothing wrong with the entry and clue.

@Barry Ancona

Oh Barry, be nice. 

I was just adding info as to what linear algebra is, in case Jim wasn't aware.

@Colby Hawkins There's the expression cross your t's and dot your i's meaning to pay close attention to details. 

How did you type the i without a dot, by the way? 

With DAT for 41D and [Iditarod] in the clue for 1A and an i and a dot you have the ingredients of some serious wordplay. Anyone?

@JohnWM

I KNEW that looked weird!

(Also, nice. 😂)

@HeathieJ 

I know what you mean by time being out of whack.

Time absolutely flew for me from early November to mid January.  Since then it's been moving as slowly as an old man trying to send back soup at a deli.
